Had they really explicitly breached a regulation, the FIA would have
prosecuted and penalised them. Fundamentally, what happened is that
McLaren, in a technical request to the FIA officials, requested the
possibility of adding such a component, raising some suspition as
wether it was allowed or not. In the end, what happened was a change
in the testing regulations &quot;From round two in Malaysia such devices
must be removed before the car undergoes the floor deflection test.&quot;

In all cases where there was a technical cheat, the teams were heavily
penalised, and that combined with a lack of even a reprimand to
Ferrari shows they were not cheating.

I'm not saying you can cheat if you can hide it (even though the FIA
just sanctioned that Thursday in Paris), I'm just saying that it is
silly to summerise this whole story by saying that Ferrari is just
moaning due to it's lost (inexistent) cheat.

F1 is such a nice sport it's very annoying to see it so burdened by
fruitless accusations and hatred.
